<subSubSection id="C33311E1FFEC7F0699F7E432D256FE36" lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B96426AFFEC7F0599F7E432D205F871" blockId="41.[151,1436,1760,2011]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEC7F0599F7E432D532F8CD" bold="true" box="[198,544,1869,1895]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
Best known in 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059BE1E432D425F8CD" box="[720,823,1869,1895]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
, where it is fairly common along roadsides in humid forests on the northern mountain range at 
<quantity id="4CD1EF8FFFEC7F059BBDE40BD407F824" box="[652,789,1908,1934]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="325.0" valueMax="450.0" valueMin="200.0">200–450 m</quantity>
, but also known from scattered specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059C69E40BD7C0F81E" name="Costa Rica" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F0599EEE4E5D651F81E" box="[223,323,1946,1972]" name="Panama" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Panama</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059860E4E5D686F81E" box="[337,404,1946,1972]" name="Cuba" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Cuba</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059890E4E5D525F81E" box="[417,567,1946,1972]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059B74E4E5D5D2F81E" box="[581,704,1946,1972]" name="Dominica" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Dominica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059BFCE4E5D42AF81E" box="[717,824,1946,1972]" name="Grenada" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Grenada</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059A77E4E5D4D3F81E" box="[838,961,1946,1972]" name="Colombia" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, northern and southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059C26E4E5D28AF81E" box="[1303,1432,1946,1972]" name="Venezuela" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F0599A6E4BED7E7F871" box="[151,245,1985,2011]" name="Guyana" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059830E4BED676F871" box="[257,356,1985,2011]" name="Ecuador" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEC7F059890E4BED6C9F871" box="[417,475,1985,2011]" name="Peru" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Peru</collectingCountry>
. It is likely to be more common and widespread than currently known.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96426AFFEF7F0699F7E3E8D256FE36" blockId="42.[151,1436,151,412]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F0699F7E3E8D621FF1B" bold="true" box="[198,307,151,177]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Notes:—</emphasis>
This triploid hybrid between 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069BBBE3E7D431FF1B" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Jermy &amp; T. G. Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[650,803,152,177]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interjectus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069BBBE3E7D431FF1B" box="[650,803,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. interjectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069A6DE3E7D313FF1B" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Desv." box="[860,1025,152,177]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069A6DE3E7D313FF1B" box="[860,1025,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB83F9BFFEF7F069DEBE3E7D7F7FF72" author="Jermy, A. C. &amp; Walker, T. G." pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="258 - 264" refId="ref31812" refString="Jermy, A. C. &amp; Walker, T. G. (1985) Cytotaxonomic studies of the ferns of Trinidad. Bulletin of the British Museum Natural History Botany 13: 185 - 191, 258 - 264." type="journal article" year="1985">Jermy &amp; Walker (1985)</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of cytotaxonomic studies of the ferns of 
<collectingCountry id="F33E02FAFFEF7F069A51E3C1D4DAFF72" box="[864,968,190,216]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
. It is similar in size to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069DE4E3C0D27DFF72" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Jermy &amp; T. G. Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[1237,1391,191,216]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interjectus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069DE4E3C0D27DFF72" box="[1237,1391,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. interjectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has a much denser indument abaxially on the segments, thus approaching 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069AC5E39AD38AFF54" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Desv." box="[1012,1176,229,254]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069AC5E39AD38AFF54" box="[1012,1176,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. On the other hand, 
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069CB7E39AD647FE8F" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. × pseudobifidus</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F0698DEE273D581FE8F" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Desv." box="[495,659,268,293]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F0698DEE273D581FE8F" box="[495,659,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having irregularly darkened parts on the bud and branch scales, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069837E24DD6A4FEE1" authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Desv." box="[262,438,306,331]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069837E24DD6A4FEE1" box="[262,438,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has translucent or only basally darkened scales. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2939E9FFEF7F069D15E24DD385FEE1" authorityName="Presl" authorityYear="1836" box="[1060,1175,306,331]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069D15E24DD385FEE1" box="[1060,1175,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Sticherus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
× 
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069D8DE24DD27BFEE1" box="[1212,1385,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">pseudobifidus</emphasis>
has conspicuously irregular segment lengths, a character shared by 
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069AB7E226D487FED8" box="[902,917,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">S</emphasis>
. × 
<emphasis id="B95D9E78FFEF7F069A8CE226D351FED8" box="[957,1091,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">subremotus</emphasis>
. Also, both hybrid taxa have strikingly unequally developed 2 
<superScript id="7C5CEF22FFEF7F069B29E2FFD53AFE24" attach="left" box="[536,552,384,398]" fontSize="6" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">nd</superScript>
branches, i.e., the opposite pairs of branches have different lengths.
</paragraph>
